 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=x@nuclearspace>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 207<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/9/03 12:45:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: New Space Plane Far Away.</span><hr size=1> If NASA ever needed a resurgence of funds, it's now.  Now that it's been proven beyond a shadow of a doubt the shuttle is death trap, we should consider doing a program that will replace the shuttle in the near future.  The SR-71 spy plane made it from drawing board to test flights in 33 months.  And soon after, was put into service.  It isn't unreasonable that we do the same with next generation space plane so long as we are conservative with the design and not go overboard like we did for the X-33 and Vulture Stool...err...I meant Venture Star.  A two-stage-to-orbit RLV can be made in a short period of time. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 354<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/12/03 7:26:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: New Space Plane Far Away.</span><hr size=1> Cut the Shuttle program now. Put it's funds into the OSP to push it along. Next work on the 2-stage RLV for the OSP, which is also a reusable 30 ton-LEO booster.<br>
Maybe work on an expendable booster for this mission first.<br>
<br>
The SR-71 is one example of quick R&amp;D and build I hadn't heard of. The GBU-28 laser guided bunker buster is one example, the DC-X is another.<br>
 I'll bet the HL-20/42 programs are examples of streamlined management -they were on fairly small budget, and that's one key to forcing NASA to do things cheaply: semi-starve them, but give them a clearly defined goal and set of steps on the way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brp17>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 257<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/13/03 6:49:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: New Space Plane Far Away.</span><hr size=1> The shuttle proven a deathtrap? Perhaps you were not aware, but the shuttle always had an estimated 1 in 100-250 chance of destruction, and they were willing to use it. It's been slowly getting safer, but stuff still can happen. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 356<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/13/03 9:13:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: New Space Plane Far Away.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt;A two-stage-to-orbit RLV can be made in a short period of time.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 That may still be too demanding for the present state of the art. It's possible, and there are many good dessigns that may work: the ROMBUS is sort of one, an updated version of Lockheed's Starclipper is another (both versions drop recoverable tankage only on the way up.)<br>
<br>
 Another option is something like the 2 stages which lift the spaceplane in the SLI images. The first one is simplest, since it drops at a low speed, and doesn't need fancy TPS or return to launch site provisions. Note that this uses an expendable third stage to throw the plane up. This makes sense to me, since that's the hardest to recover.<br>
<br>
I think the article at the top of this thread is too pessimistic -not that NASA couldn't find a way to waste a few decades on the OSP, but it doesn't have to be like that.<br>
