<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; The shuttle proven a deathtrap? Perhaps you were not aware, but the shuttle always had an estimated 1 in 100-250 chance of destruction, and they were willing to use it. It's been slowly getting safer, but stuff still can happen. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It's never been any better than pre-Challenger days (as long as it's well above freezing). They fixed the slight flaw that sub-freezing weather can cause the SRBs to malfunction, and did some other small things and some managerial changes, but nothing about the basic vehicle changed at all.<br>
Those quotes about odds for a failure never said it all. 90% of those failure scenarios resulted in complete loss of vehicle and crew, and that was never in doubt and nothing could be done about it except a radical change in design -at least forget solids in favor of liquid strap-ons, and drop the cargo to near-zero with a crew escape module.<br>
<br>
 In that way, the words &quot;Death Trap&quot; are chosen very carefully and in full knowledge of the facts of the situation. You strap yourself into a contraption with many sensitive points, where in any of a number of cases a single flaw results in everything being lost. Is that not a death trap?<br>
<br>
They were willing to use it because it's easier to convince crews, politicians and taxpayers that it's fixed and is the best, most natural and efficient way of doing the job, rather than ask for more funding to do a complete from-the-bottom-up change in operational philosophy. You must then make a really good vehicle which unfortunately doesn't pay for your huge bureaucracy and pay the politicians with factories in their voting districts, and may force you to admit that you've been robbing the taxpayers blind all along.<br>
<br>
